05611nam a22006255i 9780226124100DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013043064  a97802261241007 a10.7208/97802261241002doi  a(DE-B1597)550224  a(OCoLC)874029264  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aUA23b.T48 2014 4aUA23 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a322.509732231 aThorpe, Rebecca U., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe American Warfare State :bThe Domestic Politics of Military Spending /cRebecca U. Thorpe. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b4 halftones, 19 line drawings, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Series on International and Domestic Institutions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tPart I. Theoretical and Historical Overview -- t1. Introduction: Perpetuating the US Military Economy -- t2. Presidential War Powers in Historical Perspective -- tPart II. World War II and the Politics of Defense Spending -- t3. World War II Military Mobilization: Origins of the Rural Defense Pork Barrel -- t4. From Shared Sacrifi ce to Local Subsidy: Dispersing Defense Benefi ts and Externalizing War Costs -- t5. Local Defense Dependence and Congressional Weapons Spending -- t6. The Distributive Politics of Defense Contracting -- tPart III. You and Whose Army? Expansive Presidential War Powers -- t7. Economic Reliance and War -- t8. Executive Independence in Military Affairs -- t9. Conclusion: The Warfare State -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow is it that the United States—a country founded on a distrust of standing armies and strong centralized power—came to have the most powerful military in history? Long after World War II and the end of the Cold War, in times of rising national debt and reduced need for high levels of military readiness, why does Congress still continue to support massive defense budgets? In The American Warfare State, Rebecca U. Thorpe argues that there are profound relationships among the size and persistence of the American military complex, the growth in presidential power to launch military actions, and the decline of congressional willingness to check this power. The public costs of military mobilization and war, including the need for conscription and higher tax rates, served as political constraints on warfare for most of American history. But the vast defense industry that emerged from World War II also created new political interests that the framers of the Constitution did not anticipate. Many rural and semirural areas became economically reliant on defense-sector jobs and capital, which gave the legislators representing them powerful incentives to press for ongoing defense spending regardless of national security circumstances or goals. At the same time, the costs of war are now borne overwhelmingly by a minority of soldiers who volunteer to fight, future generations of taxpayers, and foreign populations in whose lands wars often take place. Drawing on an impressive cache of data, Thorpe reveals how this new incentive structure has profoundly reshaped the balance of wartime powers between Congress and the president, resulting in a defense industry perennially poised for war and an executive branch that enjoys unprecedented discretion to take military action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCivil-military relationszUnited States. 70(DE-588)4020517-40(DE-627)1063177680(DE-576)208933697aGeschichte2gnd 70(DE-588)4039305-70(DE-627)1047575740(DE-576)209034408aMilitär